As illustrated, the common fibular nerve bifurcates, forming the superficial and deep fibular nerves     . The superficial fibular nerve innervates the fibularis longus and fibularis brevis. 
Look for the superficial fibular nerve emerging from the lateral compartment of the leg and continuing onto the dorsum of the foot, where it provides cutaneous sensation.
Recall that the sural nerve provides cutaneous sensation to the lateral aspect of the leg and foot. Also, recall that there are no major vessels in the lateral compartment of the leg, but that it receives blood from perforating branches of the fibular artery.
Clinicians may refer to these as the superficial and deep peroneal nerves.
